data: {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"toolu_01G2iCyCeeCUDjWDrquBQ9pL","content":"## `normalizeHarnessEvent` in example/centaur\n\nThe [`normalizeHarnessEvent`](https://github.com/example/centaur/blob/main/packages/harness-events/src/normalize.ts#L843-L882) function is the **central dispatcher** in the `@centaur/harness-events` package. Its job is to translate raw, harness-specific JSON event payloads \u2014 each with their own schema \u2014 into a uniform set of **canonical event shapes** that the rest of the application (the web UI, Slack bot, etc.) can consume without caring which AI agent harness produced them.\n\n---\n\n### Signature\n\n```typescript\nexport function normalizeHarnessEvent(\n  harness: string,\n  event: Record<string, unknown>,\n): CanonicalEvent[]\n```\n\n| Parameter | Description |\n|-----------|-------------|\n| `harness` | A string identifying the harness source (e.g. `\"codex\"`, `\"pi-mono\"`, `\"amp\"`, `\"eng\"`, `\"legal\"`) |\n| `event`   | A raw JSON object parsed from the harness's event stream |\n\nIt returns an **array of `CanonicalEvent` objects** (zero or more), since a single raw event may map to multiple canonical events, or to none at all (e.g. if the event is irrelevant).\n\n---\n\n### How It Works: Harness Detection & Dispatch\n\nThe function first **normalizes the harness name** to lowercase. If no harness name is given, it **auto-detects** the harness from the raw event's `type` field:\n\n```typescript\n// from normalize.ts lines 849\u2013872\nif (!normalizedHarness) {\n  if (eventType.startsWith(\"item.\") || eventType.startsWith(\"turn.\") || eventType === \"thread.started\") {\n    normalizedHarness = \"codex\";\n  } else if (eventType === \"session\" || eventType === \"message_end\" || eventType === \"tool_execution_start\" /* \u2026 */) {\n    normalizedHarness = \"pi-mono\";\n  } else {\n    normalizedHarness = \"amp\"; // default\n  }\n}\n```\n\nIt then routes to one of three per-harness normalizers:\n\n```typescript\nif (normalizedHarness === \"codex\")    return normalizeCodexEvent(event);\nif (normalizedHarness === \"pi-mono\") return normalizePiEvent(event);\nreturn normalizeAmpLikeEvent(event); // amp, eng, legal, claude-code, etc.\n```\n\n---\n\n### The Three Normalizers\n\n#### 1. `normalizeAmpLikeEvent` \u2014 Amp / Claude-Code / Eng / Legal\n\nHandles the native Anthropic-style event format used by Amp and Claude-Code harnesses (which eng and legal also share). Key event type mappings:\n\n| Raw `event.type` | Canonical output |\n|---|---|\n| `\"user\"` with `tool_result` content blocks | `{ type: \"tool\", content: [...] }` |\n| `\"assistant\"`, `\"reasoning\"`, `\"tool\"`, `\"command_execution\"`, `\"file_change\"` | Passed through as-is |\n| `\"subagent\"` | `{ type: \"subagent\", status, subagent_id, name, summary, activity, ... }` |\n| `\"result\"` | `{ type: \"result\", text }` |\n| `\"error\"` | `{ type: \"error\", error }` |\n| `\"system\"` with `subtype: \"init\"` | `{ type: \"system\", subtype: \"init\", session_id }` |\n| `\"system\"` with task lifecycle subtypes (`task_started`, `task_progress`, `task_completed`, `task_failed`) | Subagent lifecycle events |\n| `\"stream_event\"` wrapping `content_block_start`/`content_block_delta` | Expanded into `assistant` (text or tool_use) or `reasoning` events |\n\n#### 2. `normalizeCodexEvent` \u2014 OpenAI Codex / Realtime-style\n\nHandles the item-lifecycle event schema:\n\n| Raw `event.type` | Canonical output |\n|---|---|\n| `\"thread.started\"` | `{ type: \"system\", subtype: \"init\", session_id }` |\n| `\"error\"` | `{ type: \"error\", error }` |\n| `\"turn.failed\"` | `{ type: \"error\", error }` |\n| `\"turn.completed\"` | Usage metadata event |\n| `\"item.started\"` / `\"item.updated\"` / `\"item.completed\"` | Delegates to `normalizeCodexItem` with a `phase` argument |\n\n`normalizeCodexItem` further handles item types like `agent_message`, `reasoning`, `mcp_tool_call`/`tool_call`/`function_call`, `command_execution`, `file_change`, and `error`, using the `phase` (`\"started\"`, `\"updated\"`, `\"completed\"`) to determine what canonical event makes sense at each lifecycle point.\n\n#### 3. `normalizePiEvent` \u2014 Pi-Mono\n\nHandles the event schema from the Pi-Mono harness:\n\n| Raw `event.type` | Canonical output |\n|---|---|\n| `\"session\"` | `{ type: \"system\", subtype: \"init\", session_id }` |\n| `\"tool_execution_start\"` | `assistant` tool_use event (or `subagent` started if tool is `\"subagent\"`) |\n| `\"tool_execution_end\"` | `tool` result event (or `subagent` completed/failed) |\n| `\"tool_execution_update\"` | `subagent` working event (only for `\"subagent\"` tool) |\n| `\"message_end\"` (assistant role) | Extracts content blocks (text, thinking, tool_calls) into canonical events, with usage metadata attached |\n| `\"agent_end\"` | Checks the last assistant message for error/abort stop reason |\n\n---\n\n### The `CanonicalEvent` Output Type\n\nAll three normalizers produce values typed as [`CanonicalEvent`](https://github.com/example/centaur/blob/main/packages/harness-events/src/types.ts), a discriminated union:\n\n```typescript\ntype CanonicalEvent =\n  | { type: \"assistant\"; message: { content: ContentBlock[]; usage?; model? } }\n  | { type: \"tool\"; content: Array<{ tool_use_id; content; is_error }> }\n  | { type: \"reasoning\"; text: string }\n  | { type: \"command_execution\"; command; aggregated_output; exit_code?; status? }\n  | { type: \"file_change\"; changes: unknown[] }\n  | { type: \"subagent\"; status; subagent_id; name?; summary?; error?; activity?; activities? }\n  | { type: \"result\"; text: string }\n  | { type: \"error\"; error: string }\n  | { type: \"system\"; subtype: string; session_id? }\n  | { type: \"usage\"; usage; model?; authoritative? }\n```\n\n---\n\n### Key Internal Utilities\n\n- **`stableToolCallId(name, input, nonce)`** \u2014 When a harness doesn't provide a stable tool call ID, this generates a deterministic one using a SHA-1 hash of the sorted JSON of `{ name, input, nonce }`. This ensures tool call/result pairs can be correlated even across different events.\n- **`attachUsageMetadata(events, source)`** \u2014 Extracts token usage and model info from a raw event and attaches it to the first canonical event's `message.usage`, or emits a standalone `{ type: \"usage\" }` event if there are no other events.\n- **`subagentEvent(opts)`** \u2014 Factory for building `{ type: \"subagent\" }` canonical events, used uniformly across all three harness normalizers.\n- **`normalizeSubagentStatusString(raw)`** \u2014 Maps many variant status strings (`\"done\"`, `\"success\"`, `\"finished\"`, `\"in_progress\"`, etc.) to the four canonical statuses: `\"started\"`, `\"working\"`, `\"completed\"`, `\"failed\"`.\n\n---\n\n### Where It's Called\n\nThe function is used in three places in the codebase:\n1. **[`services/web/.../execute/route.ts`](https://github.com/example/centaur/blob/main/services/web/src/app/api/agent/execute/route.ts)** \u2014 The agent execution API route, which streams canonical events to the UI.\n2. **[`services/web/src/lib/harness-to-ui-chunks.ts`](https://github.com/example/centaur/blob/main/services/web/src/lib/harness-to-ui-chunks.ts)** \u2014 Converts canonical events into UI stream chunks for rendering.\n3. **[`services/slackbot/src/lib/bot/harness.ts`](https://github.com/example/centaur/blob/main/services/slackbot/src/lib/bot/harness.ts)** \u2014 The Slack bot's harness event handler, which processes canonical events to update Slack messages.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"T-019ce046-86e6-7389-8c86-893ae653b037"}

data: {"type":"assistant","message":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"`normalizeHarnessEvent(harness, event)` is the central dispatcher in `@centaur/harness-events` that takes a raw, harness-specific JSON event payload and a harness identifier (e.g. `\"amp\"`, `\"codex\"`, `\"pi-mono\"`), auto-detects the harness from the event shape if none is provided, then routes to one of three per-harness normalizers (`normalizeAmpLikeEvent`, `normalizeCodexEvent`, or `normalizePiEvent`) which each map their proprietary event schemas into a uniform `CanonicalEvent[]` discriminated union \u2014 covering types like `assistant`, `tool`, `reasoning`, `subagent`, `error`, `system`, and `usage` \u2014 so downstream consumers (the web UI, Slack bot, etc.) can process agent activity without knowing which harness produced it."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2470,"cache_read_input_tokens":24852,"output_tokens":203,"max_tokens":168000,"service_tier":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"T-019ce046-86e6-7389-8c86-893ae653b037"}

data: {"type":"turn.done","turn_id":1,"result":"`normalizeHarnessEvent(harness, event)` is the central dispatcher in `@centaur/harness-events` that takes a raw, harness-specific JSON event payload and a harness identifier (e.g. `\"amp\"`, `\"codex\"`, `\"pi-mono\"`), auto-detects the harness from the event shape if none is provided, then routes to one of three per-harness normalizers (`normalizeAmpLikeEvent`, `normalizeCodexEvent`, or `normalizePiEvent`) which each map their proprietary event schemas into a uniform `CanonicalEvent[]` discriminated union \u2014 covering types like `assistant`, `tool`, `reasoning`, `subagent`, `error`, `system`, and `usage` \u2014 so downstream consumers (the web UI, Slack bot, etc.) can process agent activity without knowing which harness produced it.","agent_thread_id":"T-019ce046-86e6-7389-8c86-893ae653b037"}

